Thanks!
some minor comments

Can you change this into
```
letI : Algebra (R ‚ß∏ p) (S ‚ß∏ P) := something
finrank (R ‚ß∏ p) (S ‚ß∏ P)
```
Can you explain the reason behind this change?

I find that only `Module.Finite R S` is used in the proof, so I have changed all instances of `IsNoetherian R S` in this file to `Module.Finite R S`. This might be more general and align better with mathematical conventions. Of course, in this theorem, since `R` is a Noetherian ring, `IsNoetherian R S` is equivalent to `Module.Finite R S`.
I don't think `[Nontrivial (S ‚ß∏ P)]` is nessecary? `S / P` is trivial should imply `P` is the unit ideal and thus `p` must also be the unit ideal, which cannot happen.
Is this needed? I think this is just `(inertiaDeg_pos p P).ne`.
Maybe it is `(inertiaDeg_pos p P).ne.symm`. So I think it would be more convenient to use if this theorem is kept.
There's also `(inertiaDeg_pos p P).ne'`

```suggestion
  and `p` and `P` are maximal. If `p = P ‚à© S` and `P = I ‚à© S`,
```

```suggestion
theorem eq_top_iff_of_liesOver [P.LiesOver p] : P = ‚ä§ ‚Üî p = ‚ä§ := by
```
(or `eq_top_iff_eq_top_of_liesOver`)
This holds for arbitrary algebra homomorphisms right?

```suggestion
theorem nontrivial_of_liesOver_of_ne_top (hp : p ‚â† ‚ä§) : Nontrivial (B ‚ß∏ P) :=
```

```suggestion
theorem nontrivial_of_liesOver_of_isPrime [hp : p.IsPrime] : Nontrivial (B ‚ß∏ P) :=
```

```suggestion
    (h : Q = P.map œÉ) : (B ‚ß∏ P) ‚âÉ‚Çê[A ‚ß∏ p] (C ‚ß∏ Q) where
  __ := quotientEquiv P Q œÉ h
  commutes' := by
    rintro ‚ü®x‚ü©
    exact congrArg (Ideal.Quotient.mk Q) (AlgHomClass.commutes œÉ x)
```
Using rewrite to construct data is very bad. It gives `Eq.cast` in the term that is very unusable. Consider using `Ideal.quotientEquivAlgOfEq`.
